      <!-- FAQ Section -->
      <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions: Crude Oil Tank Bottom Recovery</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between items-center">
              <span>What is a crude oil tank bottom recovery system?</span>
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed mt-3">
              A crude oil tank bottom recovery system (ORS) is a modular industrial centrifuge system designed to recover saleable crude oil from the sludge that accumulates at the bottom of storage tanks. Dolphin Centrifuge's ORS uses a 3-step process: pre-treatment and screening, de-sludging through a decanter centrifuge (down to 200 microns), and final polishing through a high-speed disc stack centrifuge (down to 1 micron, less than 1% BS&amp;W). Tank bottoms with 60% BSW can be processed to less than 0.5% BSW using this system.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between items-center">
              <span>How does centrifugal separation compare to gravity settling for crude oil recovery?</span>
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed mt-3">
              An industrial centrifuge exerts a centrifugal force up to 10,000 times the force of gravity, causing near-instant separation of oil, water, and solids. Gravity settling (heat-and-settle) is much slower, recovers less oil, and leaves significant amounts of saleable crude trapped in sludge. Centrifugal processing reduces sludge volume, increases oil yield, reduces tank cleaning frequency, and can even break emulsions that gravity alone cannot separate.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between items-center">
              <span>What configurations are available for the Dolphin ORS?</span>
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed mt-3">
              Dolphin Centrifuge's Oil Recovery System is available in two configurations. The skid-mounted system uses three separate skids (pre-treatment, decanter de-sludging, and disc stack polishing) designed for indoor installation in existing buildings. The containerized system is housed in a prefabricated shipping container with built-in service cranes, lighting, surge tanks, and servicing tools, making it ideal for remote field locations with minimal infrastructure. Both configurations can process up to 2 BPM of tank bottom crude oil.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between items-center">
              <span>What is the ROI on a crude oil tank bottom recovery centrifuge system?</span>
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed mt-3">
              Based on Dolphin Centrifuge's case study processing crude oil at 0.76 BPM with 25% oil content in tank bottoms, the system produces approximately 170 barrels of sale oil per day. At $25 per barrel, that generates around $4,250 in daily revenue or $85,000 per month (based on 16 hours/day operation, 20 working days/month). With higher oil content (56%), daily revenue reaches $9,250 and monthly revenue reaches $185,000. The payback period is typically very short given these revenue figures.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-semibold text-[#1B3A5C] cursor-pointer list-none flex justify-between items-center">
              <span>What factors affect crude oil centrifuge separation efficiency?</span>
              <span class="text-[#E8A317] transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] leading-relaxed mt-3">
              Three primary factors affect ORS efficiency. First, processing temperature: heavier oils are best processed at 180 degrees Fahrenheit while lighter oils process well at 145 degrees Fahrenheit. Second, homogeneity of the process crude oil: solids must be kept in suspension through continuous agitation to prevent equipment overload and ensure consistent separation. Third, chemical and polymer and demulsifier selection: emulsion-breaking agents may be needed for slop oils with significant emulsion phases where heating and centrifugation alone may not achieve the desired level of separation. Proper control of these factors ensures consistent, high-quality separation performance.
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>

